==Jamaican Creole==
===Etymology===
Reportedly derived from '''[[bum]] [[cloth]]''', a cloth used to clean the [[anus]]<!--this is "blodclat": , or from [[blood]] cloth, a reference to cloth used to catch [[menstrual]] blood prior to the invention of [[tampon]]s and similar devices.-->

===Alternative forms===
*[[bumboclot]], [[bumbaclat]], [[bumbaklaat]], [[bumba clot]], etc.

===Interjection===
'''bumbaclot'''

#(''coarse slang'') An expression of annoyance, disgust, or dismay.

===References===
*[http://niceup.com/patois.txt Mike Pawka's Rasta/Patois Dictionary]
*[http://www.reggaemovement.com/History/patois.htm Colleen Sullivan, Jamaican Patois, Speech 214 - Rhetoric of Reggae]: "As in any language, Rastas also have words to express anger that are considered curses. An interesting point to make about the Rasta talk curses are that they are very natural in origin which coincides with the beliefs of the Rastafarian people. The worst possible way to insult a Jamaican is to refer to them as an excretion from the human body. What seems to be the most dominant curse is to refer to someone as a 'Ras clot' 'bongo clot,' or 'bumba clot.' In some contexts, the term 'clot' does mean cloth but, in this context, calling someone one of these words is like saying they came from a blood clot and not an ovum, from their mother's womb."